---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";
import NavBar from "../components/NavBar.astro";

const installCommand =
  "codex plugin marketplace add dianedef/ShipFlow --ref main --sparse .agents/plugins --sparse plugins/shipflow";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Install ShipFlow for Codex"
  description="How to add the ShipFlow marketplace source, install the shipflow plugin, and start using ShipFlow in Codex."
>
  <main class="page-shell">
    <NavBar />

    <section class="section">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Install ShipFlow</p>
        <h1 class="page-title">One marketplace source, one plugin, one first command.</h1>
        <p>
          ShipFlow is distributed as one Codex plugin named <code>shipflow</code>.
          You add the marketplace source once, install the plugin from the Codex
          plugin directory, and start with one plain instruction.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="doc-grid">
        <article class="doc-card">
          <h3>1. Add the marketplace source</h3>
          <p>
            This tells Codex where the ShipFlow plugin marketplace lives in the
            public repository.
          </p>
          <pre><code>{installCommand}</code></pre>
        </article>

        <article class="doc-card">
          <h3>2. Restart Codex</h3>
          <p>
            Restart Codex so the new marketplace source is loaded into the
            plugin directory.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="doc-card">
          <h3>3. Install the plugin</h3>
          <p>
            Open the plugin directory, choose the <code>ShipFlow</code>
            marketplace, then install the <code>shipflow</code> plugin.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="doc-card">
          <h3>4. Start with one plain instruction</h3>
          <p>
            The first useful command is:
          </p>
          <pre><code>$shipflow help me choose the right workflow</code></pre>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="cta-panel">
        <p class="eyebrow">What you get now</p>
        <h2>The public plugin is intentionally lightweight.</h2>
        <p>
          Today the plugin gives you the ShipFlow entrypoint, the pack catalog,
          packaging/install guidance, and bundled public intent routing for the
          first `shipflow-main` capability set. When a workflow needs the full
          internal corpus, ShipFlow can point you to the optional complete-corpus
          bootstrap path instead of pretending the plugin already contains every
          private reference.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-actions">
          <a class="button button-primary" href="/skills/shipflow">Open the shipflow skill page</a>
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="/skill-modes">Read the workflow cheatsheet</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="doc-grid">
        <article class="doc-card">
          <h3>If you need the full corpus</h3>
          <p>
            Some workflows still need the optional complete ShipFlow source tree.
            The plugin can route you there explicitly when that happens.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="doc-card">
          <h3>If you want the pack roadmap</h3>
          <p>
            ShipFlow keeps one public plugin first. Internal packs remain
            packaging infrastructure until they are genuinely portable and ready
            for public installation.
          </p>
          <a class="doc-action" href="/docs">Open the docs overview</a>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
